  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. These laws and frameworks are designed to prevent the illegal process of making large amounts of money generated by criminal activity, such as drug trafficking or terrorist funding, appear to have come from a legitimate source. Here are some of the key international efforts to combat money laundering:\n\n1. The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) - Also known as the Vienna Convention, it was the first international legal instrument to address money laundering.\n\n2. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) - Established in 1989 by the G7, the FATF is an intergovernmental body that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. The FATF's recommendations, known as the 40 Recommendations, provide a comprehensive framework of measures to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n3. The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000) - Also known as the Palermo Convention, it includes provisions to combat money laundering related to organized crime.\n\n4. The United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003) - This convention includes measures to prevent and combat corruption, which can be closely related to money laundering.\n\n5. The European Union Directives on Money Laundering - The EU has issued several directives aimed at preventing the use of the financial system for the purpose of money laundering and terrorist financing, which member states are required to implement into their national laws.\n\n6. The Basel Committee on Banking Supervision - While not a legal framework, the Basel Committee has issued guidance on preventing money laundering and terrorist financing within the banking sector.\n\nCountries around the world have adopted these international standards and have implemented their own anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations. These typically include requirements for financial institutions to perform customer due diligence, maintain records, report suspicious activities, and implement internal compliance programs.\n\nIt's important to note that while international laws and frameworks set the standards, the actual enforcement of anti-money laundering laws is carried out by individual countries through their legal systems and supervisory authorities. International cooperation is also crucial in tracking and preventing the flow of illicit funds across borders.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
